subject: Phillip Lorenzo
value: @pllearns, I liked having on this project because even though your time had to be split over 2 other teams, you still checked in with us several times every day to see how we were doing. And not just code wise but also culturally, your attention to the space we shared as a big team of 3 smaller teams was great. Your technical skills came into play more than you were giving yourself credit for as well. You helped us work through the problems we got stuck on and you helped make sure our code was clean and easy to read, instilling good code-readability practices. I think you made an excellent team lead for the blackjack-crew.

subject: Phillip Lorenzo
value: Whoooo hooo! We finally got to do a project together!  So stoked that we got this opportunity and looking forward to the next one .  I really appreciated your last minute askingof  the right question, and also the way you modeled being a good learner.  You really approached the whole thing, as you do everything from what I've observed, with an inspiring humility and curiosity. It was so evident in that moment because you obviously didnt have the same familiarity with the code that the three of us did, but you still managed to come up with the right question, and then you "showed your work" and broke down how you got there.  I feel like one thing I'll definitely take away from this week is the idea that when you're dealing with multiple code bases you really have to look at things as discrete chunks of code rather than trying to understand the whole immediately. One thing, that I think you kind of learned towards the end of the week,  which I think might help your culture and contribution scores is that as an 'advanced player' I think our focus should be on helping the person with the least technical skill and relieving some of that burden from the more technically skilled people on the team.  I saw you kind of pairing and cog-apping on Friday morning, and I would just encourage you to do that earlier in the game.  In particular, in retrospect I got the feeling (because they're right next door to me) that Isis, and Mo were kind of on the same wavelength  but that Robert might have needed more support.    I think it might have benefited everyone for you to have honed in on that early and spent some time pairing with him and helping him get to the level that his teammates were at.

value: I want to work with you because you have the ultimate culture personality. You don't just lead, you inspire. You bring order, organization, and reassurance to everyone. With gentle reminders you keep us focused and pushing forward. I would want to work with you more if you find that balance in letting people have autonomy, and freedom, but not sacrafice structure. The circumstances of being in two teams stretched interpretation of this scenario thin, so weigh this advice with a grain of salt. In a situation when people say "We're good, we're okay, we got it" perhaps give them the space those statements imply, but find some way to stay engaged regardless. How? I'm not sure. But when you DO discover the answer to this, you'll be amongst the greats when it comes to leadership. I wish I could have programmed with you to have a better read of your technical skills and comment on your software development. Perhaps take it upon yourself to make more hard-coded rules on time-management so you can fit those slots in. Autonomy is nice, don't sacrifice it, but structure is required to fairness not just to others, but to yourself.

They cared for the quality of our working relationship, and paid attention to it.  They acted in integrity. They helped to create and maintain clear accountabilities. They stood firm in their domain and power, and respected the domains of others.  They helped explain everything to the detail.

I would like to work more with you if you can create balance between taking the support role and also taking care of yourself.  Don't slow the project down for the sake of others, and don't take the role or responsibility of making sure that everyone is satisfied.
